Hi @Renzo-Olivares many thanks for your detailed response.

Just to be sure we're on the same page on what I think is a bug is I've attached a second example without the initial text, two videos, the first showing the behaviour on Windows Desktop, Web (Chrome) and Android (physical 24 Ultra), the second showing navigating and using backspace on the parent text field on Chrome, and some brief notes I made whilst debugging in EditableText.  In the bottom right hand corner of the videos it shows the key presses on the physical keyboard.

On Windows using the arrow or backspace key causes the unexpected behaviour (where the child text field content is overwritten with the parent text field content) and navigating the parent textfield also causes problems in the child text field.

Interestingly on Web it works fine and exactly as expected when performing actions on the parent or child text field (can use the arrow and backspace keys in the parent and child text fields without any unexpected outcomes).

On Android it works fine when using the software keyboard but when using the physical keyboard the physical delete key works fine but the physical arrow keys cause the problem (the physical android device shown is mirrored to my desktop, hence having access to the physical keyboard).

The use case is interactive widgets within a text field using a widget span, in this example I've replicated a very simple table I would want to embed into a textfield which is a seperate widget with a textfield for each cell, and embedded into the parent textfield using an widgetspan (this is obviously not a table widget I would use in a real app, but hopefully shows an example of how I'd like to embed widgets with textfields into a parent textfield).

I thought it was a bug as the behaviour is as expected in some of the examples above but not others.  I'm not up to speed on the inner workings of the Flutter frameworks itself but in the brief notes I've attached from trying to debug EditableText it seems that the parent textfield is intercepting the key presses even when they happen in the child textfield but then taking action on the child EditableText instance.

I've tried various different designs such as using focus nodes but it always results in the same problem.

The only workaround I've found if when clicking on the TextField to render it as an overlay as I assume this then takes it out into a speraete widget tree (if I understand how overlays work correctly).

Hope this all makes sense, let me know if not or if I can provide any other examples of information.  

